1
00:00:00,467 --> 00:00:02,457
I think the idea behind a tuxedo...

2
00:00:02,512 --> 00:00:05,187
is kind of the woman's point of
view that men are all the same.

3
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:07,274
We might as well
dress them that way.

4
00:00:08,043 --> 00:00:12,011
To me, a wedding is the joining
together of a beautiful, glowing bride...

5
00:00:12,081 --> 00:00:13,739
and some guy.

6
00:00:14,350 --> 00:00:18,011
The tuxedo is a wedding safety
device, created by women...

7
00:00:18,087 --> 00:00:20,246
because they know that men
are undependable.

8
00:00:20,456 --> 00:00:22,183
So in case the groom chickens out...

9
00:00:22,257 --> 00:00:25,554
everybody takes one step over,
and she marries the next guy.

10
00:00:25,828 --> 00:00:28,897
That's why the wedding vow isn't,
"Do you take Bill Simpson?"

11
00:00:28,964 --> 00:00:31,089
It's, "Do you take this man?"

12
00:00:37,106 --> 00:00:39,140
Leave a message.
I'll call you back. Thanks.

13
00:00:39,274 --> 00:00:42,901
Jerry? Joe Davola.

14
00:00:45,681 --> 00:00:48,375
I have a hair on my tongue.

15
00:00:48,450 --> 00:00:49,847
Can't get it off.

16
00:00:49,918 --> 00:00:52,009
You know how much I hate that?

17
00:00:52,187 --> 00:00:55,415
Of course you do.
You put it there.

18
00:00:55,491 --> 00:00:57,559
I know what you said about me,
Seinfeld.

19
00:00:57,626 --> 00:01:00,752
I know you bad-mouthed me
to the execs at NBC.

20
00:01:00,829 --> 00:01:03,454
Put the kibosh on my deal.

21
00:01:03,532 --> 00:01:06,601
Now I'm gonna put the kibosh on you.

22
00:01:07,036 --> 00:01:09,070
You know I've kiboshed before.

23
00:01:09,638 --> 00:01:12,673
And I will kibosh again.

24
00:01:19,114 --> 00:01:21,307
- So, what do you think?
- About what?

25
00:01:21,417 --> 00:01:23,485
- About the opera.
- I don't wanna go.

26
00:01:23,552 --> 00:01:25,950
- You gotta go.
- I don't like the opera.

27
00:01:26,021 --> 00:01:28,919
What are they singing for?
Who sings?

28
00:01:29,158 --> 00:01:31,783
You got something to say, say it.

29
00:01:32,361 --> 00:01:34,929
You don't understand.
That's the way they talk in Italy.

30
00:01:34,997 --> 00:01:37,156
They sing to one another.

31
00:01:43,572 --> 00:01:44,900
All right. All right.

32
00:01:44,973 --> 00:01:47,166
That's their way.
You listen to the language.

33
00:01:47,242 --> 00:01:49,537
It's got that sing-songy quality to it.

34
00:01:49,611 --> 00:01:52,009
It's the language, Jerry.
The language.

35
00:01:52,381 --> 00:01:56,110
- So why don't they talk like that now?
- It's too hard to keep up.

36
00:01:56,185 --> 00:01:58,879
You know, they got...
They were tired.

37
00:01:59,788 --> 00:02:01,185
- Better get that.
- Yeah.

38
00:02:01,256 --> 00:02:03,483
- It's me.
- Come on up.

39
00:02:03,559 --> 00:02:05,889
- So?
- I don't know.

40
00:02:05,961 --> 00:02:10,521
Come on. It's opening night.
Black-tie, Pagliacci. The great clown.

41
00:02:10,599 --> 00:02:13,862
The great, sad, tragic clown,
like you.

42
00:02:15,337 --> 00:02:17,564
Well, that's very flattering.

43
00:02:17,639 --> 00:02:19,866
How'd you get tickets?
They're impossible to get.

44
00:02:19,942 --> 00:02:22,101
Well, I have many associates.

45
00:02:23,278 --> 00:02:25,471
I don't know.
Opera, it's not my kind of thing.

46
00:02:25,581 --> 00:02:27,740
Then I'm gonna call
the whole thing off.

47
00:02:27,816 --> 00:02:30,544
Wait a minute. What about
George, Susan and Elaine?

48
00:02:30,619 --> 00:02:32,744
- Why do you need me?
- You're the nucleus...

49
00:02:32,821 --> 00:02:36,322
the straw that stirs the drink.
You're the "magliana."

50
00:02:36,492 --> 00:02:39,083
I guess if I'm the magliana,
I should go.

51
00:02:39,161 --> 00:02:41,092
All right. All right.

52
00:02:41,163 --> 00:02:42,560
- Good.
- Hey.

53
00:02:42,631 --> 00:02:43,959
You got the tickets, right?

54
00:02:44,032 --> 00:02:47,795
- No, I don't have them on me.
- What? That's why I came over here.

55
00:02:47,870 --> 00:02:50,097
My friend's got them.
I'll pick them up tomorrow.

56
00:02:50,172 --> 00:02:54,402
I was gonna surprise Joey with them.
You got an extra one, right?

57
00:02:54,476 --> 00:02:56,043
Oh, yeah!

58
00:02:56,111 --> 00:03:00,773
So I finally get to meet
your pal Joey.

59
00:03:01,250 --> 00:03:03,375
- It's killing you, isn't it?
- Yeah.

60
00:03:03,452 --> 00:03:06,680
So Joey's a great lover of the opera.

61
00:03:06,755 --> 00:03:08,846
Listen...

62
00:03:09,491 --> 00:03:11,024
I got news for you.

63
00:03:11,093 --> 00:03:13,024
It's nice to be involved
with somebody...

64
00:03:13,095 --> 00:03:16,028
who's interested in something
other than Nick at Nite.

65
00:03:17,933 --> 00:03:19,933
You know, he's got a grip on reality.

66
00:03:20,002 --> 00:03:23,435
He's... He's happy. He's well-adjusted.

67
00:03:33,081 --> 00:03:34,580
Looking forward to meeting him.

68
00:03:34,650 --> 00:03:36,377
I gotta go.

69
00:03:36,885 --> 00:03:38,213
Where? What's the rush?

70
00:03:38,287 --> 00:03:40,446
To surprise Joey.
I've never been to his place.

71
00:03:40,522 --> 00:03:43,557
- I'm just gonna pop in.
- Good, men love that.

72
00:03:46,094 --> 00:03:47,593
Hey.

73
00:03:48,964 --> 00:03:50,793
You got a message, buddy.

74
00:03:50,866 --> 00:03:52,456
It could be from that blond.

75
00:03:55,938 --> 00:03:59,030
Jerry? Joe Davola.

76
00:04:01,109 --> 00:04:02,733
I have a hair on my tongue.

77
00:04:09,918 --> 00:04:12,509
What am I gonna do?
He's gonna put the kibosh on me.

78
00:04:12,588 --> 00:04:16,647
- He's crazy, out of his mind!
- Steady, steady! Now, calm yourself!

79
00:04:16,725 --> 00:04:19,794
He's supposed to be on medication.
He told me he was on medication.

80
00:04:19,861 --> 00:04:22,589
- What happened to his medication?
- Quiet! Now let me think.

81
00:04:22,898 --> 00:04:25,694
I'm gonna call the cops.
That's what I'm doing. The cops.

82
00:04:25,834 --> 00:04:27,902
Why?! They're not gonna
do anything!

83
00:04:27,970 --> 00:04:29,901
They're the cops.
They gotta do something.

84
00:04:29,972 --> 00:04:33,007
He'll put the kibosh on me. Do you
know what it is to be kiboshed?

85
00:04:34,109 --> 00:04:37,440
- Kibosh.
- It's a terrible mistake.

86
00:04:37,512 --> 00:04:41,013
He thinks I ruined some deal at NBC.
I don't know anything about it.

87
00:04:41,083 --> 00:04:44,516
- Call and tell him that.
- That... That's what I'll do.

88
00:04:44,586 --> 00:04:48,713
I'll just call him and tell him.
That's all I'll do. Right.

89
00:04:48,924 --> 00:04:52,516
He's a human being.
I'll talk to him. He'll understand, right?

90
00:04:52,594 --> 00:04:54,457
Yeah.

91
00:04:54,529 --> 00:04:56,028
Don't mention my name.

92
00:04:59,268 --> 00:05:01,700
Oh, I got the machine.

93
00:05:01,770 --> 00:05:04,395
- What's his message like?
- Nice.

94
00:05:04,673 --> 00:05:06,673
Hello, Joe. Listen,
this is Jerry Seinfeld.

95
00:05:06,742 --> 00:05:10,505
I think there's been a huge, colossal
misunderstanding.

96
00:05:10,579 --> 00:05:13,273
Big. Big.

97
00:05:13,348 --> 00:05:15,848
If we could just talk,
we could straighten this out...

98
00:05:15,917 --> 00:05:18,815
so call me back. Bye.

99
00:05:22,024 --> 00:05:23,648
Joey?

100
00:05:24,459 --> 00:05:26,322
Joey?

101
00:05:44,913 --> 00:05:48,744
Oh, God. It's you. You scared me.

102
00:05:48,817 --> 00:05:51,613
Good. Fear's our most
primal emotion.

103
00:05:53,655 --> 00:05:55,450
You left your door open.

104
00:05:55,557 --> 00:05:58,251
I know. I like to encourage intruders.

105
00:06:03,231 --> 00:06:04,457
What is all this?

106
00:06:04,533 --> 00:06:05,895
Do you like it?

107
00:06:05,967 --> 00:06:10,026
My home is a shrine to you.

108
00:06:10,672 --> 00:06:12,501
Where did you get all these pictures?

109
00:06:12,574 --> 00:06:15,666
I took them myself
with a telephoto lens.

110
00:06:16,378 --> 00:06:19,208
Coming out of your office,
your apartment.

111
00:06:19,381 --> 00:06:21,073
Shopping.

112
00:06:21,149 --> 00:06:22,807
Showering.

113
00:06:24,319 --> 00:06:26,944
Showering?

114
00:06:27,022 --> 00:06:28,851
I develop them myself
in my darkroom.

115
00:06:28,924 --> 00:06:31,219
Would you..? Would you like to see?

116
00:06:32,394 --> 00:06:35,292
In the darkroom?
Oh, no, thank you.

117
00:06:35,364 --> 00:06:37,694
Not right now.

118
00:06:37,766 --> 00:06:40,892
I'm a day person.

119
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:47,370
Are..? Are you all right?

120
00:06:47,709 --> 00:06:49,470
Why?

121
00:06:49,978 --> 00:06:53,275
Well, I don't know.
You just don't...

122
00:06:53,348 --> 00:06:56,315
- seem yourself.
- Who am I?

123
00:06:57,419 --> 00:07:00,647
- Who am I supposed to be?
- That's a good question.

124
00:07:00,722 --> 00:07:04,349
Good question. It's very existential.

125
00:07:04,426 --> 00:07:08,087
Who are you? Who am I? Well...

126
00:07:08,597 --> 00:07:09,925
What are you doing here?

127
00:07:09,998 --> 00:07:12,828
Oh, nothing. I just stopped by
to chat.

128
00:07:12,901 --> 00:07:15,333
You know, shoot the breeze.

129
00:07:15,404 --> 00:07:18,632
Were you able to get those Pagliacci
opera tickets from your friend?

130
00:07:18,707 --> 00:07:20,536
I'm really looking forward to it.

131
00:07:22,944 --> 00:07:26,605
No, he couldn't get them.
We're not going.

132
00:07:27,048 --> 00:07:28,638
Really?

133
00:07:30,886 --> 00:07:34,319
Oh, damn it.
I just remembered I gotta go.

134
00:07:34,389 --> 00:07:39,119
I left something on. The gas,
the lights, the water in the tub.

135
00:07:39,194 --> 00:07:42,161
Something is on somewhere,
so I'm just gonna get the...

136
00:07:44,166 --> 00:07:47,258
Do you know the story of Pagliacci,
Nedda?

137
00:07:48,437 --> 00:07:50,095
I'm Elaine.

138
00:07:50,205 --> 00:07:53,240
He's a clown whose wife
is unfaithful to him.

139
00:07:54,843 --> 00:07:57,844
Do you think I'm a clown, Nedda?

140
00:07:58,613 --> 00:08:02,649
Do I think you're a clown?
No. Not if it's bad to be a clown.

141
00:08:02,717 --> 00:08:06,776
If it's bad to be a clown, then
you are definitely not a clown.

142
00:08:06,855 --> 00:08:11,858
But if it's good to be a clown, then I
would have to rethink the whole thing.

143
00:08:12,561 --> 00:08:15,425
You've betrayed me with another,
haven't you, Nedda?

144
00:08:15,497 --> 00:08:17,724
Who is he? I want you
to tell me who he is.

145
00:08:17,799 --> 00:08:20,197
I want his name. Tell me his name.

146
00:08:20,268 --> 00:08:23,963
Oh, like any man would
ever look at me. Come on.

147
00:08:24,039 --> 00:08:26,334
I'm gonna get out of here.

148
00:08:26,408 --> 00:08:28,476
Pagliacci kills his wife.

149
00:08:28,543 --> 00:08:32,135
See? Now that's terrible. That is...
That's not a nice thing to do at all.

150
00:08:32,214 --> 00:08:35,943
I would assume... I don't know how
this Pagliacci thing turns out.

151
00:08:36,017 --> 00:08:40,076
But I would assume that there was
big, big trouble for that clown.

152
00:08:40,322 --> 00:08:41,650
You're not leaving.

153
00:08:47,496 --> 00:08:49,393
But, officer, he threatened me.

154
00:08:49,464 --> 00:08:51,156
I don't understand.
That's not right.

155
00:08:51,233 --> 00:08:54,700
What if it was the president
of the U.S? I bet you'd investigate.

156
00:08:54,769 --> 00:08:58,737
So, what's the difference?
I'm a comedian of the United States.

157
00:08:59,074 --> 00:09:01,938
And I'll tell you, I'm under
just as much pressure.

158
00:09:02,277 --> 00:09:05,642
All right. Thanks anyway.
Okay, bye.

159
00:09:08,750 --> 00:09:11,410
- Who is it?
- It's George.

160
00:09:15,290 --> 00:09:18,257
- You're locking the door now?
- Yeah.

161
00:09:28,436 --> 00:09:30,299
Well, well. Look at you.

162
00:09:31,840 --> 00:09:34,602
It's a little skimpy there, isn't it?

163
00:09:36,077 --> 00:09:38,441
You know the last time
I wore this thing?

164
00:09:38,513 --> 00:09:39,841
Six years ago.

165
00:09:39,915 --> 00:09:42,313
When I made that toast
at Bobby Leighton's wedding.

166
00:09:42,384 --> 00:09:44,577
Oh, that was a bad toast.

167
00:09:44,653 --> 00:09:46,152
It wasn't that bad.

168
00:09:46,221 --> 00:09:48,846
I never heard anybody curse
in a toast.

169
00:09:49,491 --> 00:09:51,582
I was trying to loosen them up
a little bit.

170
00:09:51,660 --> 00:09:53,489
There were old people there.

171
00:09:53,562 --> 00:09:57,621
All the relatives.
You were like a Redd Foxx record.

172
00:09:58,300 --> 00:10:00,595
At the end of the toast,
nobody even drank.

173
00:10:00,669 --> 00:10:03,533
They were just standing. They were
just frozen. People...

174
00:10:04,539 --> 00:10:07,836
That might have been
one of the worst all-time toasts.

175
00:10:07,909 --> 00:10:11,240
Still, her father didn't have
to throw me out like that.

176
00:10:11,313 --> 00:10:13,847
He could've asked me to leave.
He had me in a headlock.

177
00:10:15,150 --> 00:10:16,683
Susan's not going tonight.

178
00:10:16,985 --> 00:10:18,712
What do you mean, not going?
Why not?

179
00:10:18,787 --> 00:10:21,082
She had to pick up a friend
at the airport.

180
00:10:21,156 --> 00:10:23,087
It cost me $100, this ticket.

181
00:10:23,158 --> 00:10:26,022
- Why didn't she pay for hers?
- That's a very good question.

182
00:10:26,561 --> 00:10:29,459
She and I go to dinner,
she doesn't even reach for the check.

183
00:10:29,531 --> 00:10:32,293
All I'm asking for is a reach.
Is that so much to ask for?

184
00:10:32,367 --> 00:10:34,128
It's nice to get a reach.

185
00:10:37,505 --> 00:10:40,369
- Who is it?
- It's me!

186
00:10:41,476 --> 00:10:44,044
Why are you locking the door now?

187
00:10:44,446 --> 00:10:45,945
Because of Davola. Get in here.

188
00:10:46,014 --> 00:10:48,082
What the..?

189
00:10:49,918 --> 00:10:52,543
- How come you're not dressed?
- I am dressed.

190
00:10:52,621 --> 00:10:55,519
- You're going like this?
- Yeah. I want you to hear something.

191
00:10:55,590 --> 00:10:59,820
- You said people dress up for opera.
- Well, people do. I don't.

192
00:11:01,363 --> 00:11:03,931
If you're going like that,
I'm not going like this.

193
00:11:03,999 --> 00:11:07,557
Wait a minute! Do you think
I'm comfortable here?

194
00:11:07,869 --> 00:11:10,130
I can't change. I got no clothes here.

195
00:11:10,205 --> 00:11:12,569
You gotta go like that.
I can't go like this alone.

196
00:11:12,641 --> 00:11:15,608
Why should I be uncomfortable
because my apartment is closer?

197
00:11:15,677 --> 00:11:17,836
That's not the issue. We're friends.

198
00:11:17,912 --> 00:11:20,003
If I gotta be uncomfortable,
you gotta too.

199
00:11:20,081 --> 00:11:23,582
All right. I'll wear this. It's bad enough
I gotta go to the opera...

200
00:11:23,652 --> 00:11:26,550
I gotta sit next to Ozzie Nelson
over here.

201
00:11:26,755 --> 00:11:29,517
Would you turn that down?
What is that crap?

202
00:11:29,591 --> 00:11:31,420
It's Pagliacci.

203
00:11:31,493 --> 00:11:33,083
Oh, beautiful.

204
00:11:33,161 --> 00:11:35,729
We got a little problem here.
We got two extra tickets.

205
00:11:35,797 --> 00:11:38,092
- Why, what happened?
- Susan isn't going...

206
00:11:38,166 --> 00:11:42,202
and Elaine's friend isn't going.
- Fantastic. We'll scalp the tickets.

207
00:11:42,270 --> 00:11:44,930
We can make maybe 500 a ticket.

208
00:11:45,006 --> 00:11:46,539
- Really?
- Oh, yeah.

209
00:11:46,608 --> 00:11:49,233
People are looking for tickets here?

210
00:11:49,711 --> 00:11:54,441
Are you kidding? Opening night,
Pavarotti in Pagliacci?

211
00:11:54,516 --> 00:11:57,710
- We're gonna clean up.
- Oh, man, I knew I'd love the opera.

212
00:11:57,786 --> 00:12:01,219
- Yeah, right.
- Come on, let's go get the tickets.

213
00:12:01,289 --> 00:12:04,256
Listen, I gotta wait for Elaine.
I'll meet you at the theater.

214
00:12:04,325 --> 00:12:06,256
- All right, yeah.
- Isn't scalping illegal?

215
00:12:06,327 --> 00:12:08,258
Oh, yeah.

216
00:12:24,879 --> 00:12:28,972
You sprayed him in the eyes
with Binaca?

217
00:12:31,453 --> 00:12:34,021
Cherry Binaca. It's new.

218
00:12:34,255 --> 00:12:36,880
See, I don't get that.
First they come out with regular.

219
00:12:36,958 --> 00:12:38,491
A year later, they have cherry.

220
00:12:38,560 --> 00:12:41,891
They know we like cherry. Start with
cherry. Then come out with regular.

221
00:12:42,263 --> 00:12:45,196
It was like I didn't know him.
He was a different person.

222
00:12:45,366 --> 00:12:47,400
You should hear the message
from my nut.

223
00:12:48,036 --> 00:12:51,071
Where's George and Kramer?
I wanna get inside already.

224
00:12:51,139 --> 00:12:53,230
I feel very vulnerable.

225
00:12:54,075 --> 00:12:55,642
What you doing?
That's my quarter.

226
00:12:55,710 --> 00:12:59,007
- No, it's not. It's mine.
- I was just flipping it. That's mine.

227
00:12:59,080 --> 00:13:00,511
No, I dropped it. It's mine.

228
00:13:00,582 --> 00:13:04,015
All right, you want it, take it,
but don't try and tell me it's yours.

229
00:13:04,085 --> 00:13:05,618
Well, it is mine.

230
00:13:05,954 --> 00:13:07,749
What, you think I care
about the money?

231
00:13:07,822 --> 00:13:09,617
Is that what you think? I'll show you.

232
00:13:09,691 --> 00:13:11,452
Look at this. Here's a dollar. Look.

233
00:13:11,526 --> 00:13:13,150
That's how much
I care about money.

234
00:13:13,228 --> 00:13:16,661
You think I care about money.
That's how much I care about money.

235
00:13:16,765 --> 00:13:18,696
- Why don't you get lost?
- Why don't you?

236
00:13:18,767 --> 00:13:20,926
- Because I was standing here.
- Oh, yeah?

237
00:13:21,002 --> 00:13:22,694
Yeah.

238
00:13:27,041 --> 00:13:30,110
I kind of like this opera crowd.
